text.i: Mixed Use Building – 316 Bloor Street West, Toronto

page.text: LEA Consulting Ltd. (LEA) was retained by 316 Bloor West Toronto Developments Ltd. to prepare a
Transportation Impact Study for a proposed mixed-use development consisting of approximately 256
sq.m. of at-grade retail and 535 condominium units, located at 316 Bloor Street West (herein referred to
as the “subject site”). The residential units are exclusively bachelor and 1-bedroom units and are geared
to urban residents that want to live in an area where they can work, play and shop without the use of an
automobile. Due to the proximity of the University of Toronto St. George campus, it may also attract
university students. A parking supply of 50 spaces is proposed. The subject site is located within the area
bounded by Bloor Street West to the south, Spadina Road to the west, Lowther Avenue to the north, and
Madison Avenue to the east. Figure 1.1 illustrates the site location in context of the surrounding road

text.i: Mixed Used Building – 316 Bloor Street West, Toronto

page.text: The development proposal is for 535 residential condominium units, and approximately 256 m
grade retail. The proposed site statistics are summarized in Table 1-1.
Vehicular access to the subject site will be to/from Madison Avenue which is a one-way southbound
only road. Subsequently, inbound traffic will approach along Madison Avenue from the north, while
outbound site traffic can only exit to Madison Avenue and connect to Bloor Street West. The site plan for
the proposed development is illustrated in Figure 1-2.

text.i: Mixed Used Building – 316 Bloor Street West, Toronto

page.text: The study area includes the signalized intersection of Bloor Street West and Spadina Road, as well as the
unsignalized intersection of Bloor Street West and Madison Avenue. Existing lane configurations within
the study area are shown in Figure 2-1.
Bloor Street West is a major east-west Avenue that operates within the study area with a four-lane
cross-section. The roadway intersects Spadina Road/Avenue at a signalized intersection. Turning lanes

text.i: Mixed Used Building – 316 Bloor Street West, Toronto

page.text: are provided in the eastbound and westbound directions at the Spadina Avenue intersection. No posted
speed limit was identified and is assumed at a 50 km/hr.
Spadina Avenue (Spadina Road north of Bloor Street West) is a major north-south arterial which
operates with a four-lane cross section in the study area. No posted speed limit was identified and is
Madison Avenue is a local road running north-south, with the southern extent terminating at Bloor
Street West. It is a wide road which provides one lane of travel in general, one-way (southbound) due to
the presence of on street parking. However at Bloor Street West it is wide enough to accommodate
exclusive left and right turning vehicles, even with on-street parking. This road has a posted speed limit
The proposed development is well served by transit. Spadina Subway Station and bus station is located
adjacent to the rear of the subject site, on Spadina Road. This station provides access to both the Line 1
Yonge-University-Spadina subway, and the Line 2 Bloor-Danforth subway. Spadina station is also
served by the 510 Spadina streetcar route featuring the TTC’s new Flexity Outlook high-capacity
vehicles. TTC bus route 127 Davenport serves this station. St. George Subway Station is located
approximately 250 m to the east of the subject site, and provides access to the Line 1 Yonge-University-
Spadina Subway, Line 2 Bloor-Danforth Subway, as well as TTC bus route 26 Dupont. A map of TTC
routes can be seen in Figure 2-2.

text.i: Mixed Used Building – 316 Bloor Street West, Toronto

page.text: Several major cycle routes are available on nearby streets. This area is heavily frequented by cyclists,
including along Bloor Street West and throughout the Annex neighbourhood. A map of existing routes in
the vicinity of the subject site can be seen in Figure 2-3.

text.i: Mixed Used Building – 316 Bloor Street West, Toronto

page.text: Turning movement counts for all intersection within the study area were conducted by LEA on
Thursday, November 13, 2014 during peak a.m. and p.m. periods. Peak hour traffic at Spadina Avenue at
Bloor Street West occurred from 8:00 – 9:00 a.m. and from 4:30 p.m. to 5:30 p.m. Peak hour volumes at
the Madison Avenue and Bloor Street West intersection occurred at 8:15-9:15 a.m. and 5:00 – 6:00 p.m.
The existing balanced traffic volumes for the both weekday peak hours are presented in Figure 2-4. A
southbound vehicle queue length survey was also conducted to determine if Madison Avenue traffic
generates vehicle queues back to the proposed site access. The queue data is summarized in Appendix A
and the results indicate no issues or concerns with vehicle queuing.
Intersection capacity analysis was undertaken for the subject intersections using Synchro 8.0 (Build 803)
in accordance with the methodology outlined in the Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) 2000. The

page.text: analysis parameters have been inputted in accordance with the City of Toronto’s Guidelines for Using
Synchro 7.0. A peak hour factor of 0.90 and 0.95 was applied for the a.m. and p.m. peak hour analyses,
respectively. The signal timing plan for the traffic signal at the intersection of Bloor Street West and
Spadina Avenue was obtained from the City of Toronto and is included in Appendix A.
The Spadina Avenue at Bloor Street West intersection operates with a fixed timed mode, with an 85-
second cycle during the a.m. peak period, and a 90-second cycle during the pm. peak period.
Table 2-1 summarizes the levels of service for the signalized intersections under both weekday peak
hours of existing traffic conditions. Detailed Synchro outputs for the existing traffic condition analysis
can be found in Appendix B. The intersection capacity analysis suggests that the Spadina Avenue at
Bloor Street West intersection operates with an acceptable level of service during both weekday peak
hours. No movement experiences any notable congestion or delays.

page.text: For the purposes of this study, a five year study horizon was selected for analysis of future traffic
conditions (to year 2019). The following sub-sections outline our assumptions for the future background
traffic scenario, which represents future traffic conditions at the intersections within the study area
without the proposed development application. The future background traffic volumes therefore reflect
general corridor growth in the study area, as well as other specific developments expected to be built in
the surrounding area within the study horizon.
General corridor traffic growth was determined through comparison of historical and current traffic data
for the intersection of Bloor Street West and Spadina Avenue. The date and source of the reviewed data
are summarized in Table 3-1. From 2005 to 2014, there has been a decrease and minimal increase in
traffic volumes during the weekday a.m. and p.m. peak hour; respectively. In order to provide a more
conservative analysis, a 0.5% annual growth rate was therefore assumed for all movements at the
Spadina Avenue and Bloor Street West intersection and to the through movements on Bloor Street at

page.text: The proposal is for a 42 storey mixed-use building, with retail on the ground floor and 535 residential
condominium units comprising the remainder. Approximately 256 m
of ground floor retail area is
proposed. The residential units are exclusively bachelor and 1-bedroom units. This development will
attract urban residents that want to live in an area where they can work, play and shop without the use of
an automobile. Due to the proximity of the University of Toronto St. George campus directly to the
south, it may also attract university students. As such, parking demand in the building is expected to be
minimal and it is proposed that the development will offer 50 resident parking stalls, with no visitor
parking. This is further supported by the excellent transit system that serves the proposed development.
The proposed development is located at Madison Avenue and Bloor Street West, Toronto. This area,
known as The Annex, is an area heavily frequented by pedestrians, cyclists, and transit users, and Bloor
Street West is a major east-west street connection. The Annex is a neighbourhood well known for its
accessibility. Spadina Subway Station and bus station is located adjacent to the rear of the subject site, on
Spadina Road. This station provides access to both the Line 1 Yonge-University-Spadina subway, and
the Line 2 Bloor-Danforth subway. Spadina station is also served by the 510 Spadina streetcar route
featuring the TTC’s new Flexity Outlook high-capacity vehicles. TTC bus route 127 Davenport serves
this station. St. George Subway Station is located approximately 250 m to the east of the subject site, and
also provides access to the Line 1 Yonge-University-Spadina Subway, Line 2 Bloor-Danforth Subway,
as well as TTC bus route 26 Dupont. Being at the junction of the north-south and the east-west subway
lines allows residents of this development the opportunity to travel by subway in all directions. This level
of subway service is only offered at one other location in the City, at Yonge and Bloor.
In addition to excellent transit service, the subject site is located in an area of high walkability with a
dense residential population in proximity. The Annex neighbourhood is also known for its large cycling
population, and the subject site is easily accessed from the surrounding community and the University of
Vehicular parking specifications for this proposed development are set out in City of Toronto By-law
